, Wiltshire, England":"Wilton, Wiltshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1180–Aft 1225":"1180–efter 1225","1180–1225":"1180–1225","1187–1260":"1187–1260","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1135–Male":"1135–Afdød","1135–Female":"1135–Afdød","Aft 1225":"efter 1225","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wilton, Wiltshire, England":"Wilton, Wiltshire, England"},"nl":{"1180–Aft 1225":"1180–na 1225","1180–1225":"1180–1225","1187–1260":"1187–1260","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1135–Male":"1135–Overleden","1135–Female":"1135–Overleden","Aft 1225":"na 1225","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wilton, Wiltshire, England":"Wilton, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1180–Aft 1225":"1180–after 1225","1180–1225":"1180–1225","1187–1260":"1187–1260","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1135–Male":"1135–Deceased","1135–Female":"1135–Deceased","Aft 1225":"after 1225","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1187":"1187","1175":"1175","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1180":"1180","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Wilton, Wiltshire, England":"Wilton, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for someone who habitually wore a distinctive pair of boots or gaiters, from Old French <i>hosed</i>, <i>hoset</i>, <i>housé</i>, Middle English <i>hosey</i>, <i>hus(s)y</i>,‘booted, gaitered’ (from Latin <i>hosatus</i>).","English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>hus(e)wyf</i> ‘mistress of a family; wife of a householder’ (a compound of Old English <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>wīf</i> ‘woman’). Though originally a woman's name, it is often found as a male surname, presumably in a derogatory sense. The vocabulary word became <i>hussie</i>, with the meaning ‘disreputable woman’, in the 16th century; the surname, however, is not associated with this meaning.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"Ameria","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A blend of two medieval names: <i>Emilia</i> (which is of Latin origin:  see  Emily  ) and the Latinized Germanic   Amalia .   Henry Fielding  is sometimes credited with having coined it for the heroine of his novel Amelia (  1751 ), but forms such as <i>Meelia</i>, <i>Amaly</i> and <i>Aemelia</i> occur from the 17th century onwards."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ameria Anna Hussey was born in 1180, in London, Middlesex, England, her father, Richard Hussey, was 45 and her mother, Mabel de Talbot, was 46. She married Roger de Mutton in 1200, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1225, in her hometown."},"et":{"1180–Aft 1225":"1180–pärast 1225","1180–1225":"1180–1225","1187–1260":"1187–1260","1175–1225":"1175–1225","1200–1250":"1200–1250","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","Aft 1225":"pärast 1225","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224